message_1:
Solve the following system of linear equations using QR decomposition:
\begin{align*}
2x + y - z &= 5\\
-x + 3y + 2z &= -1\\
3x - 2y - z &= 3
\end{align*}

message_2:
To solve the given system of linear equations using QR decomposition, we first need to rewrite the system in the matrix form Ax = b, where A is the matrix of coefficients, x is the column vector of variables, and b is the column vector of constants.

The given system can be written as:

A = \begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & -1 \\
-1 & 3 & 2 \\
3 & -2 & -1
\end{bmatrix}

x = \begin{bmatrix}
x \\
y \\
z
\end{bmatrix}

b = \begin{bmatrix}
5 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we will perform QR decomposition on matrix A, such that A = QR, where Q is an orthogonal matrix and R is an upper triangular matrix.

Using the Gram-Schmidt process, we can find the orthogonal basis for the column space of A:

u1 = \begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix}

u2 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
3 \\
-2
\end{bmatrix} - (\frac{u1^T \cdot u2}{||u1||^2})u1 = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
3 \\
-2
\end{bmatrix} - \frac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{12}{14} \\
\frac{17}{14} \\
\frac{-11}{14}
\end{bmatrix}

u3 = \begin{bmatrix}
-1 \\
2 \\
-1
\end{bmatrix} - (\frac{u1^T \cdot u3}{||u1||^2})u1 - (\frac{u2^T \cdot u3}{||u2||^2})u2 = \begin{bmatrix}
-1 \\
2 \\
-1
\end{bmatrix} - \frac{1}{14}\begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix} - \frac{1}{6}\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{12}{14} \\
\frac{17}{14} \\
\frac{-11}{14}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
-\frac{1}{3} \\
\frac{2}{3} \\
-\frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix}

Now, normalize the orthogonal basis vectors to obtain the orthonormal basis:

q1 = \frac{u1}{||u1||} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{14}}\begin{bmatrix}
2 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} \\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{14}} \\
\frac{3}{\sqrt{14}}
\end{bmatrix}

q2 = \frac{u2}{||u2||} = \frac{14}{\sqrt{726}}\begin{bmatrix}
\frac{12}{14} \\
\frac{17}{14} \\
\frac{-11}{14}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{6}{\sqrt{182}} \\
\frac{17}{\sqrt{182}} \\
-\frac{11}{\sqrt{182}}
\end{bmatrix}

q3 = \frac{u3}{||u3||} = \frac{3}{\sqrt{6}}\begin{bmatrix}
-\frac{1}{3} \\
\frac{2}{3} \\
-\frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \\
\frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can form the orthogonal matrix Q and the upper triangular matrix R:

Q = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} & \frac{6}{\sqrt{182}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{14}} & \frac{17}{\sqrt{182}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\
\frac{3}{\sqrt{14}} & -\frac{11}{\sqrt{182}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
\end{bmatrix}

R = \begin{bmatrix}
\sqrt{14} & \frac{20}{\sqrt{14}} & -\frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} \\
0 & \frac{\sqrt{182}}{2} & \frac{5\sqrt{182}}{6} \\
0 & 0 & \frac{\sqrt{6}}{3}
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can solve the system Rx = Q^Tb:

Q^Tb = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{14}} & \frac{3}{\sqrt{14}} \\
\frac{6}{\sqrt{182}} & \frac{17}{\sqrt{182}} & -\frac{11}{\sqrt{182}} \\
-\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}} & \frac{2}{\sqrt{6}} & -\frac{1}{\sqrt{6}}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}
5 \\
-1 \\
3
\end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix}
\frac{19}{\sqrt{14}} \\
\frac{5}{\sqrt{182}} \\
\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}}
\end{bmatrix}

Now, we can solve the upper triangular system Rx = Q^Tb using back substitution:

z = \frac{\frac{4}{\sqrt{6}}}{\frac{\sqrt{6}}{3}} = 2

y = \frac{\frac{5}{\sqrt{182}} - \frac{5\sqrt{182}}{6} \cdot 2}{\frac{\sqrt{182}}{2}} = 1

x = \frac{\frac{19}{\sqrt{14}} - \frac{20}{\sqrt{14}} \cdot 1 + \frac{2}{\sqrt{14}} \cdot 2}{\sqrt{14}} = 1

So, the solution to the system of linear equations is x = 1, y = 1, and z = 2.
